New Standard, new ways to initialize objects! With C++20, we get a handy way of initializing data members. The new feature is called designated initializers and might be familiar to C programmers. Let’s have a look at this small feature: The basics Designated Initialization is a form of Aggregate Initialization. As of C++20, an Aggregate type:: is an array type or, is a class type that:
has no private or protected direct non-static data members has no user-declared or inherited constructors has no virtual, private, or protected base classes has no virtual member functions In a basic form in C++20, you can write: Type obj = { .designator = val, .designator = val2, ... }; // or Type obj = { .designator { val }, .designator { val2 }, ... };
